{{Infobox medical condition (new) | name = Eosinopenia | image = Eosinophil 2.jpg | caption = An eosinophil in peripheral blood | | pronounce = | field = | synonyms = | symptoms = | complications = | onset = | duration = | types = | causes = | risks = | diagnosis = | differential = | prevention = | treatment = | medication = | prognosis = | frequency = | deaths = }} '''Eosinopenia''' is a form of [[agranulocytosis]] where the number of [[eosinophil granulocyte]]s is lower than expected. [[Leukocytosis]] with eosinopenia can be a predictor of bacterial infection.<ref name="pmid12829215">{{cite journal |vauthors=Gil H, Magy N, Mauny F, Dupond JL |title=[Value of eosinopenia in inflammatory disorders: an "old" marker revisited] |language=French |journal=Rev Med Interne |volume=24 |issue=7 |pages=431–5 |year=2003 |pmid=12829215 |doi= 10.1016/S0248-8663(03)00138-3|url=http://linkinghub.elsevier.com/retrieve/pii/S0248866303001383}}</ref> It can be induced by stress reactions, [[Cushing's syndrome]], or the use of [[steroid]]s.<ref name="titleMonocytopenia/Eosinopenia/">{{cite web|url=http://www.pathology.vcu.edu/education/hematology/wbc/non-neoplastic/ben-ezra/sld019.htm |title=Monocytopenia/Eosinopenia/ |accessdate=2008-02-17 |work= |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080116055418/http://www.pathology.vcu.edu/education/hematology/wbc/non-neoplastic/ben-ezra/sld019.htm |archivedate=2008-01-16 |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref> Pathological causes include burns and acute infections.
