'''James Carleton Bell''' (December 11, 1872 – February 28, 1946) was an American educational psychologist and professor of education at the [[City College of New York]].<ref name=nyt>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1946/03/01/archives/j-carleton-bell-psychologist-73-education-professor-emeritus-at.html |title=J. CARLETON BELL, PSYCHOLOGIST, 73; Education Professor Emeritus at City College Is Dead in Florida--A Leader in Field Taught While Still a Student Organized School Service Bureau |date=1946-03-01 |work=The New York Times |access-date=2018-05-19 |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref>
==Biography== Bell was born in [[Mount Vernon, Ohio|Mount Vernon]], [[Ohio]], on December 11, 1872. After graduating from [[Mount Vernon High School (Ohio)|Mount Vernon High School]] in 1891, he received his B.A. from [[Denison University]] in 1896. He then attended the [[University of Berlin]] and the [[University of Leipzig]] in [[Germany]] before enrolling at [[Harvard University]]. He received his A.M. and Ph.D. from Harvard in 1903 and 1904, respectively. He then taught [[Latin]] at the [[Boston Latin School]] for one year before taking a position as instructor in [[experimental psychology]] at [[Wellesley College]] for two years; then, he became director of the experimental psychology lab at the [[Brooklyn Training School for Teachers]]. In 1912, he joined the faculty of the [[University of Texas]], where he was Professor of the Art of Teaching from then until September 1916, when he returned to the Brooklyn Training School for Teachers.<ref name=nyt/><ref>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5XgmAQAAIAAJ |title=University of Texas Record |last=Texas |first=University of |date=1913 |publisher=The University |pages=524 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |date=1916 |title=Notes and News |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FxpRAAAAYAAJ |journal=The Journal of Philosophy |language=en |publisher=Journal of Philosophy, Incorporated |pages=476}}</ref> In 1910, he was one of four founding [[editors-in-chief]] of the ''[[Journal of Educational Psychology]]'', along with [[William Bagley (educator)|William Bagley]], [[Carl Seashore]], and [[Guy Montrose Whipple]].<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Williams |first=Joanna P. |date=January 1978 |title=Analysis of the Journal of Educational Psychology: Toward a definition of educational psychology |url=http://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/00461527809529182 |journal=Educational Psychologist |volume=12 |issue=3 |pages=290–296 |doi=10.1080/00461527809529182 |issn=0046-1520}}</ref> Bell served as the journal's managing editor from 1910 to 1920.<ref name=nyt/><ref>{{Cite journal |last=Wineburg |first=Sam |date=2004-03-01 |title=Crazy for History |url=https://academic.oup.com/jah/article/90/4/1401/758431 |journal=Journal of American History |language=en |volume=90 |issue=4 |pages=1401–1414 |doi=10.2307/3660360 |issn=0021-8723}}</ref> In 1924, he joined the faculty of the [[City College of New York]] (CCNY) as Professor of Education. From 1926 to 1929, he was director of the CCNY-affiliated high school [[Townsend Harris Hall]]. He died of a [[coronary thrombosis]] in [[Winter Park, Florida|Winter Park]], [[Florida]], on February 28, 1946.<ref name=nyt/>
