'''Joe McCarroll''' is a conservative campaigner in [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]]. He has campaigned [[anti-abortion|against abortion]], [[LGBT Rights]] and [[divorce]].
He was part of the editorial group of [[The Brandsma Review]].<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.bradyco.ie/brandsma/archive/issue40/e.htm |magazine=[[The Brandsma Review]] |volume=7 |issue=6 |dead-url=yes |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030426164446/http://www.bradyco.ie/brandsma/archive/issue40/e.htm |archive-date=26 April 2003 |title=We're RC- But Not Religiously Correct |first=Nick |last=Lowry |quote=Our editorial group now consists of ourselves (Nick and Mary Lowry), Joe McCarroll, Fr Brendan Purcell, David Manly, Louis Power and Peadar Laighléis |date=December 1998 – January 1999 |df= }}</ref>
==Divorce== {{see also|Fifteenth Amendment of the Constitution of Ireland}}
Joe McCarroll, along with [[Des Hanafin]], is a founding member, and vice-chairman,<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=Anglo-Celt|page=8|title=Monaghan Anti-Divorce Meeting|date=23 November 1995}}</ref> of the Anti-Divorce Campaign which unsuccessfully campaigned for a No vote in the [[Fifteenth Amendment of the Constitution of Ireland|1995 divorce referendum]].<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=The Irish Times|page=5|date=31 August 1995|first=Carol|last=Coulter|title=Opponents of divorce prepare campaign}}</ref><ref>{{cite newspaper|newspaper=The Irish Times|date=25 January 1995|page=32|title=Anti-Divorce Committee}}</ref> He warned that if it were to pass, people would be divorced against their will.
{{quote|author=Joe McCarroll|text=Does that mean that if one partner says there is such a prospect [no reasonable prospect of reconciliation], the court is then obliged to deny a divorce? If it doesn't mean that, then you have unilateral divorce against the will of the other person<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=The Irish Times|page=12|date=16 September 1995|title=This Week They Said}}</ref>}}
The referendum was passed by a slim margin, and after an unsuccessful court challenge by Des Hanafin, was signed into law in June 1996.<ref name="it58604">{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/news/result-of-divorce-referendum-is-formally-signed-by-high-court-1.58604|title=Result of divorce referendum is formally signed by High Court|last=Newman|first=Christine|date=15 June 1996|newspaper=[[The Irish Times]]|accessdate=29 April 2015}}</ref>
==Abortion== {{see also|Abortion in the Republic of Ireland|Pro Life Campaign}}
Joe McCarroll co-founded the [[Pro Life Campaign]] in 1992, and was its chairman until December 2015. He was active in the PLC, giving opening and closing statements at seminars.<ref>{{cite tweet|number=249458441746276353|user=CoraSherlock|title=Opening remarks by Dr Joe McCarroll, Chair of Pro Life Campaign at start of national seminar #plc2012|date=22 September 2012|author-link=Cora Sherlock}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://prolifecampaign.ie/main/our-work/our-people/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150429172645/http://prolifecampaign.ie/main/our-work/our-people/|archive-date=29 April 2015|quote=Dr. Joseph McCarroll is Chairperson of the Pro Life Campaign.He is also an author and social commentator.|title=Our People|publisher=Pro Life Campaign}}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet|number=249500404763734016|user=CoraSherlock|title=Dr Joe McCarroll giving closing address at #plc2012 after a very successful seminar.|author-link=Cora Sherlock|date=22 September 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet|number=717817162191282178|user=CoraSherlock|author-link=Cora Sherlock|title=@daithigorman What? Joe McCarroll is no longer Chairperson, hasn't been since December 2015. @JimJRedmond @Colmogorman|date=6 April 2016}}</ref>
===2002 Abortion referendum=== {{See also|Twenty-fifth Amendment of the Constitution Bill, 2002 (Ireland)}}
While chairman of the Pro Life Campaign he called for a 'yes' vote in the [[Twenty-fifth Amendment of the Constitution Bill, 2002 (Ireland)]],<ref>{{cite newspaper|newspaper=The Irish Times|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/chairman-urges-hard-work-to-ensure-yes-vote-1.1051319|date=22 February 2002|first=Lorna|last=Siggins|title=Chairman urges hard work to ensure Yes vote}}</ref> which was rejected by the people in the vote. He said the proposed amendment was "not anti-woman" and would "put the unborn on the social radar screen" so that women with an unexpected pregnancy could be supported, and that the amendment would provide a very good barrier against "anyone smuggling in abortion and describing it as medical treatment."
==LGBT rights== In 1993, as national secretary of [[Family Solidarity]], he campaigned against the [[LGBT rights in the Republic of Ireland#Law regarding same-sex sexual activity|decriminalisation of homosexuality]], calling it "unnatural",.<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=The Irish Times|page=4|date=23 April 1993|title=The case against homosexual law reform|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/archive/1993/0423/Pg012.html|last=McCarroll|first=Joseph}}{{paywall}}</ref> In 2015, in the lead up to the [[Thirty-fourth Amendment of the Constitution of Ireland|marriage equality referendum]], he campaigned against it, and called for a no vote.<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=Broadsheet.ie|url=http://www.broadsheet.ie/2015/05/12/slippery-slope-1993/|title=Slippery Slope, 1993|date=12 May 2015}}</ref>
==Personal life== He has a PhD.
