[[File:Gretchen F. Hahnen in The Delineator in 1903.png|thumb]] '''Mellin's Food Company''' was a maker of '''Mellin's Food for Infants and Invalids''' in [[Boston, Massachusetts]].
==History== The company started when the English food chemist [[Gustav Mellin]] developed an [[infant formula]] in 1866.<ref name ="Oxford">{{cite encyclopedia |author=Andrew Smith |title= |year=2013 |publisher= |page= |encyclopedia=The Oxford Encyclopedia of Food and Drink in America | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DOJMAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA102 |isbn= }}</ref> Mellin's formula was a simplified version of one which had been recently invented by the German chemist [[Justus von Liebig]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Brock |first=William H |date=1997 |title=Justus Von Liebig: The Chemical Gatekeeper |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=VugoemP2th0C&pg=PA247&lpg=PA247&dq=Mellin%27s+Food+Liebig&source=bl&ots=M78aVe41E0&sig=DgdPHQzcPIMZmlGkEyxa8lz7dQg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwid2r_PkOHTAhWBDcAKHS0XBvoQ6AEIWTAO#v=onepage&q=Mellin's%20Food%20Liebig&f=false |location= |publisher=Cambridge University Press |page=247 |isbn=0-521-56224-4 |author-link= }}</ref> It wasn't a total nutritional supplement, the powder was diluted with [[cow's milk]] and water and was called a "milk modifier".<ref name ="Oxford"/> It was a "soluble, dry extract of wheat, [[malted barley]] and [[bicarbonate of potassium]]."<ref>{{cite book |author=Jacqueline H. Wolf |title=Don't Kill Your Baby |year=2001 |publisher=[[Ohio State University Press]] |page=163 |quote= | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hHbTDVfWNU4C&pg=PA163 |isbn= }}</ref> The formula was advertised with the slogan: "Mellin's Food for Infants and Invalids: The only perfect substitute for Mother's Milk".<ref>{{cite book |last=Bentley |first=Amy |date=2014 |title=Inventing Baby Food: Taste, Health, and the Industrialization of the American Diet |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=tNMkDQAAQBAJ&pg=PA24&dq=mellin%27s+food+for+infants+and+invalids&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjZ9sj0lOHTAhWfF8AKHf1fAPwQ6AEIOjAE#v=onepage&q=mellin's%20food%20for%20infants%20and%20invalids&f=false |location= |publisher=University of California Press |page=24 |isbn=978-0-520-27737-3 }}</ref> [[File:MellinsAirship.jpg|thumb|right|The "Mellin's Airship" being flown by [[Stanley Spencer (aeronaut)|Stanley Spencer]] in 1902.]] In 1902, the Mellin Food Company sponsored the construction of the United Kingdom's first [[airship]] by [[Stanley Spencer (aeronaut)|Stanley Spencer]]. The completed airship carried an advertisement for Mellin's Food on its envelope. On 22 September 1902, Spencer flew the "Mellin's Airship" (officially named "Airship No 1") across London from [[Crystal Palace, London|Crystal Palace]] to [[Harrow, London|Harrow]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.blimpinfo.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/01/Stanley-Spencer-Airship-No-1.pdf |title=Stanley Spencer’s Airship No 1 Makes First Powered Flight in Great Britain |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website=www.blimpinfo.com |publisher= |access-date=8 May 2017}}</ref>
